<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-604-996  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 604 996.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  June 1990 v27 n6 p30(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Aerospace and defense. (Looking ahead to a single Europe in 1992)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Esch, Karl.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Integrating members' individual capabilities into a unified,noncontentious entity is the biggest challenge facing the membersof the European Communities in the aerospace area.andP;  A number ofmergers in West Germany and and France, may indicate, however,that those two countries want to develop their own economies ofscale to remain competitive in what has become a stagnatingdefense market and an increasingly profitable civilian aerospacemarket.andP;  There are two examples of European cooperativeness in theaerospace field: European Space Agency, a consortium of thenational space research agencies of 13 countries, and ArianespaceSA, which builds and launches the Ariane rockets.andP;  One of thebiggest questions today is what will happen in the defense sectoras rising costs and changing politics force a restructuring of theEuropean defense industry.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Aerospace IndustryMilitaryDefense ContractsEuropean Economic Community.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Workload breakdown of Ariane 4 rocket contractors by country.andO;(table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>